{"parentUuid":null,"isSidechain":true,"userType":"external","cwd":"D:\\refactoring\\ops5k_x64","sessionId":"cbf36e9e-1564-47ed-964c-9c92d2e54eee","version":"2.1.61","gitBranch":"main","agentId":"a4b8c499a345e20d1","slug":"expressive-strolling-blum","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":"Design a detailed implementation plan for replacing non-thread-safe C functions with their Windows _s (secure) equivalents in a large C codebase (OPS5K industrial system).\n\n## Context\nThe CLAUDE.md instructions (in Japanese) say:\n- Goal: Make minimal changes, don't change logic, replace non-thread-safe functions with thread-safe ones according to `unsafe_to_safe.csv`\n- Replacement targets can be confirmed in `.hooks`\n- DON'T DO: Change logic code, Change unrelated parts, Change unrelated comments\n\n## Mapping (from unsafe_to_safe.csv)\n```\nstrtok() → strtok_s()\nasctime() → asctime_s()\nctime() → ctime_s()\ngmtime() → gmtime_s()\nlocaltime() → localtime_s()\nstrerror() → strerror_s()\ngetenv() → getenv_s()\nrand() → rand_s()\nsrand() → rand_s()\ntmpnam() → tmpnam_s()\n```\n\n## Pre-commit Hook\nThe `.hooks/.denylist` contains regex patterns like `\\bstrtok\\s*\\(` that scan all tracked `src/` files. The pre-commit hook runs `pre_commit_denylist.py` which will BLOCK commits containing any of these unsafe function calls.\n\n**CRITICAL**: The denylist uses `\\b` word boundary + function name + `\\s*\\(` pattern. This means:\n- `strtok(` will match (blocked)\n- `strtok_s(` will NOT match (the `\\b` before `strtok` and the `_s` after make `strtok_s` a different word)\n- Commented-out code like `//strtok(` WILL still match and be flagged\n\n## Actual Usage Found in Codebase\n\n### strtok() - 36 files, most complex\nTypical patterns:\n1. **Chained calls**: `p = strtok(str, delim); ... p = strtok(NULL, delim);`\n2. **Loop pattern**: `p = strtok(str, delim); while(p != NULL) { ... p = strtok(NULL, delim); }`\n3. **do-while**: `p = strtok(str, delim); do { ... } while((p = strtok(NULL, delim)) != NULL);`\n4. **Multiple tokens**: `p1 = strtok(buf, \" \"); p2 = strtok(NULL, \" \"); p3 = strtok(NULL, \" \");`\n\nReplacement: `strtok_s(str, delim, &context)` - needs a `char *context = NULL;` variable declared.\n\n### localtime() - 6 files\nPattern: `struct tm *date; date = localtime(&now); val = date->tm_year + 1900;`\nReplacement: `struct tm date_buf; localtime_s(&date_buf, &now);` then `val = date_buf.tm_year + 1900;` (change `->` to `.`)\nNote: Windows localtime_s has params: `errno_t localtime_s(struct tm* _Tm, const time_t* _Time)`\n\n### gmtime() - 11 files\nSame pattern as localtime. \nReplacement: `struct tm tmt_buf; gmtime_s(&tmt_buf, sec);` then change `->` to `.`\nNote: Windows gmtime_s: `errno_t gmtime_s(struct tm* _Tm, const time_t* _Time)`\n\n### getenv() - 22 files  \nPattern 1 (with NULL check): `str = getenv(\"VAR\"); if(str == NULL) ...`\nPattern 2 (direct in sprintf): `sprintf(buf, \"%s\\\\file\", getenv(\"PATH_FILE\"));`\nReplacement: `size_t len; char env_buf[256]; getenv_s(&len, env_buf, sizeof(env_buf), \"VAR\");`\n- Where NULL was checked: check `len == 0` instead\n- Where result was used directly: use `env_buf` instead\n\n### strerror() - 9 files\nPattern: `sprintf(err_cp, \"malloc(): %s\", strerror(errno));`\nReplacement: `char strerr_buf[256]; strerror_s(strerr_buf, sizeof(strerr_buf), errno);` then use `strerr_buf` in sprintf.\nNote: Windows strerror_s: `errno_t strerror_s(char* _Buf, size_t _SizeInBytes, int _ErrNum)`\n\n### ctime() - 2 files (both in memwatch.c)\nPattern: `mwWrite(\"\\nStarted at %s\\n\", ctime(&tid));`\nReplacement: `char ctime_buf[26]; ctime_s(ctime_buf, sizeof(ctime_buf), &tid);` then `mwWrite(\"\\nStarted at %s\\n\", ctime_buf);`\nNote: Windows ctime_s: `errno_t ctime_s(char* _Buf, size_t _SizeInBytes, const time_t* _Time)`\n\n### asctime(), rand(), srand(), tmpnam() - 0 active files\nNot found in active source code. No changes needed.\n\n## Important Considerations\n\n1. **Commented-out code**: The denylist will match commented-out unsafe function calls too! For example:\n   - `src/msg/cotalk/f_tlk.c` has `//struct tm *local = localtime(&t);` \n   - `src/NX_MW/opsnexus/init.c` has commented-out strerror()\n   These need to be handled - either replace in comments too, or remove the comments.\n   \n   Per CLAUDE.md: \"Don't change unrelated comment-outs\" - but if the pre-commit hook blocks them, they MUST be changed. The instruction says don't change \"comments unrelated to the replacement targets\" - these comments ARE related since they contain the target functions.\n\n2. **Already-commented safe alternatives**: Some files have commented-out _s versions:\n   - `nexus_lib.c` has `//sprintf_s(...strerror_s(...))` \n   These suggest previous attempts at migration.\n\n3. **Pointer-to-member dereference changes**: When replacing localtime/gmtime, all `->` accesses must change to `.` since we go from pointer to stack-allocated struct.\n\n4. **Variable scope**: New variables (context pointers, buffers) must be declared in the right scope - ideally at the beginning of the function block for C89 compatibility (this is a C codebase, possibly compiled with older MSVC).\n\n5. **getenv direct usage in sprintf**: Pattern like `sprintf(buf, \"%s\\\\file\", getenv(\"VAR\"))` needs careful refactoring to use a temporary buffer.\n\n## Design the Plan\nPlease design a step-by-step implementation plan, organized by function type. For each function:\n1. List all files to modify\n2. Show the exact transformation pattern\n3. Note any special cases or edge cases\n4. Consider the order of operations\n\nAlso design a verification strategy using the pre-commit hook."},"uuid":"6752faf7-1804-450f-a32f-b88612167d9e","timestamp":"2026-02-27T01:38:05.984Z"}
