ent** [18 files]:\n\n**Pattern 1: getenv with NULL check (most common)**\n| File | Calls |\n|------|-------|\n| `src\\ens\\Dll\\ledocm_dll\\dl_SubProc.c` | 1 |\n| `src\\gen\\Genset\\Genset600.c` | 2 |\n| `src\\gen\\Genset\\Genset100.c` | 2 |\n| `src\\rep\\doprct\\prc000.c` | 1 |\n| `src\\tool\\calc_dsp\\Calc_dsp.c` | 1 |\n| `src\\tool\\#sysdcnv\\sysdcnv.c` | 6 |\n| `src\\tool\\FusenTrdCnv\\FusenTrdCnv.c` | 1 |\n| `src\\tool\\SysUpdate\\SysUpdate.c` | 2 |\n| `src\\tool\\PIOTool_64\\PIOTool_64.c` | 1 |\n| `src\\tool\\slotread\\slotread.c` | 3 |\n| `src\\lib\\grphlib\\grhtgtn.c` | 2 |\n\n**Pattern 2: getenv directly inside sprintf (HIGH risk)**\n| File | Calls |\n|------|-------|\n| `src\\lnk\\jorepfl\\jorepfl.c` | 1 |\n| `src\\lnk\\johubsts\\johubsts.c` | 1 |\n| `src\\sys\\aomsctl2\\aomsctl2.c` | 1 |\n| `src\\sys\\aomsctl\\aomsctl.c` | 1 |\n| `src\\sys\\aoalm\\aoalm.c` | 1 |\n| `src\\tool\\GBreg\\make_GDtt.c` | 5 |\n| `src\\tool\\GBreg\\main.c` | 9 |\n| `src\\tool\\GBreg\\dump.c` | 2 |\n\n### Transformation\n\n**Windows getenv_s**: `errno_t getenv_s(size_t *requiredSize, char *buffer, size_t numberOfElements, const char *varname)`\n\n**Pattern 1 -- getenv with NULL check**:\n```c\n// BEFORE:\nchar *env_cp;\nenv_cp = getenv(\"PATH_EXCEL\");\nif (env_cp == NULL) { /* error */ }\nsprintf(cmd_c, \"\\\"%s\\\\Excel.exe\\\" ...\", env_cp);\n\n// AFTER:\nsize_t env_len;\nchar env_buf[256];\ngetenv_s(&env_len, env_buf, sizeof(env_buf), \"PATH_EXCEL\");\nif (env_len == 0) { /* error */ }\nsprintf(cmd_c, \"\\\"%s\\\\Excel.exe\\\" ...\", env_buf);\n```\n\n**Pattern 2 -- getenv directly in sprintf**:\n```c\n// BEFORE:\nsprintf(cnfname_c, \"%s\\\\name\\\\%s\", getenv(S_FILE_PATH), S_JFREPFL_DEFNAME_P);\n\n// AFTER:\n{ size_t env_len; char env_buf[256]; getenv_s(&env_len, env_buf, sizeof(env_buf), S_FILE_PATH);\n  sprintf(cnfname_c, \"%s\\\\name\\\\%s\", env_buf, S_JFREPFL_DEFNAME_P); }\n```\n\nOr with function-level declarations:\n```c\nsize_t env_len;\nchar env_buf[256];\n...\ngetenv_s(&env_len, env_buf, sizeof(env_buf), S_FILE_PATH);\nsprintf(cnfname_c, \"%s\\\\name\\\\%s\", env_buf, S_JFREPFL_DEFNAME_P);\n```\n\n### Special Cases\n\n1. **Genset100.c L98** -- uses `getenv` inline in `if` condition:\n   ```c\n   if ((chk_c = getenv(\"PATH_ENSFILE\")) != NULL) {\n   ```\n   **After**:\n   ```c\n   { size_t chk_len; getenv_s(&chk_len, chk_c, sizeof_chk_buf, \"PATH_ENSFILE\"); }\n   if (chk_len > 0) {\n   ```\n   Need to check how `chk_c` is declared -- it may already be a buffer. If it is a pointer, we need a buffer.\n\n2. **Genset600.c** -- uses `getenv` return for `strcmp`:\n   ```c\n   str_cp = getenv(\"GENEDT_MODE\");\n   if (str_cp == NULL || strcmp(str_cp, \"Document_Graph\") != 0) {\n   ```\n   **After**:\n   ```c\n   size_t env_len;\n   char env_buf[256];\n   getenv_s(&env_len, env_buf, sizeof(env_buf), \"GENEDT_MODE\");\n   if (env_len == 0 || strcmp(env_buf, \"Document_Graph\") != 0) {\n   ```\n\n3. **GBreg files** -- very heavy use of `getenv` inline in sprintf. Each needs extraction to a separate line. When multiple `getenv` calls appear in the same function, they can share a single `env_buf`/`env_len` pair since calls are sequential.\n\n4. **johubsts.c L237** -- uses `strcpy(z_szOpsFile, getenv(\"PATH_FILE\"))`. Needs:\n   ```c\n   size_t env_len;\n   char env_buf[256];\n   getenv_s(&env_len, env_buf, sizeof(env_buf), \"PATH_FILE\");\n   strcpy(z_szOpsFile, env_buf);\n   ```\n\n5. **Lelogf.c** -- already partially migrated. The `/* ... */` block at L406-412 contains `getenv(` which triggers the denylist. Options:\n   - Change `getenv(` to `getenv_s(` inside the block comment\n   - Or remove the block comment entirely since the replacement code follows\n\n6. **Comment-only files** -- change `getenv(` to `getenv_s(` within the comment text.\n\n---\n\n## Phase 6: strtok() -> strtok_s() [38 files, 346 occurrences, HIGHEST complexity]\n\n### Windows strtok_s Signature\n`char *strtok_s(char *strToken, const char *strDelimit, char **context)`\n\nThe key addition is the `char **context` parameter, which replaces the internal static state of `strtok()`.\n\n### Core Transformation Patterns\n\n**Pattern A -- First call + continuation calls**:\n```c\n// BEFORE:\nchar *tok;\ntok = strtok(buf, \" ,\");\n... \ntok = strtok(NULL, \" ,\");\n\n// AFTER:\nchar *tok;\nchar *strtok_ctx = NULL;\ntok = strtok_s(buf, \" ,\", &strtok_ctx);\n...\ntok = strtok_s(NULL, \" ,\", &strtok_ctx);\n```\n\nThe **only change** per sequence is:\n1. Declare `char *strtok_ctx = NULL;` (or `char *context = NULL;`) at the function/block top\n2. Replace every `strtok(` with `strtok_s(` and append `, &strtok_ctx)` before the closing parenthesis\n\n### Naming Convention for Context Variable\n\nLooking at the already-present commented-out examples in `init.c`:\n- `tokh_next`, `tokv_next`, `tokt_next`, `tokp_next`, `tokgrp_next`, `toktcd_next`, `tokbuf_next`, `tokg_next`, `tokb_next`\n\nThese use a naming pattern of `{original_var_name}_next`. However, since `strtok_s` maintains state via a single context pointer across the entire chain, **only one context variable per strtok chain is needed** (not one per token variable).\n\nRecommended naming: `strtok_ctx` (simple, consistent across all files) or follow the existing commented-out convention.\n\nFor `init.c`, the commented-out code uses per-variable contexts (e.g., `tokh_next`), but technically they share the same chain, so a single context suffices. To be truly minimal and consistent, use a single `char *strtok_ctx = NULL;` per function.\n\n**However**, if a function has multiple **independent** strtok chains (parsing different buffers), each chain needs its own context. For example, if `strtok(buf1, delim)` and later `strtok(buf2, delim)` start two separate parse sequences, they need separate contexts. In practice, most functions in this codebase re-initialize by passing a non-NULL first argument to start a new chain, so a single context variable (re-used for each new chain) works.\n\n### File-by-File Categorization\n\n**High call count (priority due to volume)**:\n| File | Calls | Pattern Type |\n|------|-------|-------------|\n| `src\\sys\\aosysi\\aosysi.c` | 146 | Multiple independent chains across many functions |\n| `src\\his\\dobnkcom\\fl_bnkc01.c` | 34 | Repeated 2-token pair parsing |\n| `src\\his\\dobnkcomt\\fl_bnkc01.c` | 34 | Identical to above (copy) |\n| `src\\NX_MW\\opsnexus\\init.c` | 21 | Multiple chains, has commented-out _s examples |\n| `src\\tool\\hstsav\\hstsav.c` | 11 | Multi-chain token parsing |\n| `src\\lnk\\I-NET\\jorecs.c` | 8 | Standard chain |\n| `src\\mail\\hoemls\\hoe_rcv_ssl.c` | 8 | Standard chain |\n\n**Medium call count**:\n| File | Calls |\n|------|-------|\n| `src\\tool\\trdmov\\trdmov.c` | 6 |\n| `src\\tool\\dll\\erlgdsp\\erlgdsp.c` | 6 |\n| `src\\tool\\mssctl\\mssctl_cmdsend.c` | 6 |\n| `src\\mail\\hoemls\\hoe_rcv.c` | 6 |\n| `src\\lnk\\johubsts\\johubsts.c` | 4 |\n| `src\\sys\\aoalm\\aoalm.c` | 4 |\n\n**Low call count (2-3 calls each)**:\nAll remaining files have 2-3 calls each: `botrdls.c`, `coalm100.c`, `enq.c`, `graph.cpp`, `hstg120.c`, `mdcl160.c`, `lemmeq100.cpp`, `Legrph.c`, `LeGmsDraw.c`, `TF_valinfset.c`, `TF_subjectset.c`, `f_csvread.c`, `aomngr.c`, `jorepfl.c`, all `mssctl*` and `mssctl2*` files, `hoe_sub.c`, `ini_GS_color.c`, `ini_GS_hcpalt.c`\n\n### Special Cases\n\n1. **do-while pattern** (`enq.c` L129/159):\n   ```c\n   func_c = strtok(argv[S_FUNC],\":\");\n   do { ... } while ((func_c = strtok(NULL,\":\")) != NULL);\n   ```\n   **After**:\n   ```c\n   char *strtok_ctx = NULL;\n   func_c = strtok_s(argv[S_FUNC], \":\", &strtok_ctx);\n   do { ... } while ((func_c = strtok_s(NULL, \":\", &strtok_ctx)) != NULL);\n   ```\n\n2. **while-loop pattern** (`ShQue.c` L191-194, `erlgdsp.c`):\n   ```c\n   Token_p = strtok(FString_c, \" \");\n   Token_p = strtok(NULL, \" \");\n   while((Token_p = strtok(NULL, \" \")) != (int)NULL){\n   ```\n   **After**:\n   ```c\n   char *strtok_ctx = NULL;\n   Token_p = strtok_s(FString_c, \" \", &strtok_ctx);\n   Token_p = strtok_s(NULL, \" \", &strtok_ctx);\n   while((Token_p = strtok_s(NULL, \" \", &strtok_ctx)) != (int)NULL){\n   ```\n\n3. **Array-filling loop** (`aosysi.c` common pattern):\n   ```c\n   p_c[0] = strtok(z_buf_c, \" ,\");\n   for (i=0; i<8; i++) {\n     if (p_c[i] != NULL) p_c[i+1] = strtok(NULL, \" ,\");\n   }\n   ```\n   **After**: Add `char *strtok_ctx = NULL;` at function top, then:\n   ```c\n   p_c[0] = strtok_s(z_buf_c, \" ,\", &strtok_ctx);\n   for (i=0; i<8; i++) {\n     if (p_c[i] != NULL) p_c[i+1] = strtok_s(NULL, \" ,\", &strtok_ctx);\n   }\n   ```\n\n4. **Chained if-guarded parsing** (`aosysi.c` many locations):\n   ```c\n   p_c[0]=strtok(z_buf_c, \" ,\");\n   if (p_c[0] != NULL) p_c[1]=strtok(NULL, \" ,\");\n   if (p_c[1] != NULL) p_c[2]=strtok(NULL, \" ,\");\n   ```\n   All use the same context variable. Straightforward replacement.\n\n5. **Commented-out strtok** (`hstatst_9000.c` L1468/1470):\n   ```c\n   //exe_c = strtok(tmp_c, \" ,\") ;\n   //  wrk_c=strtok(NULL, \" ,\") ;\n   ```\n   Change to `strtok_s(` in comments.\n\n6. **Multiple independent chains in one function** (`aosysi.c` large functions):\n   Some functions in `aosysi.c` parse different buffers with `strtok`. Since each chain starts with `strtok(buf, delim)` (non-NULL first arg), a single context variable naturally resets when the first arg is non-NULL. Therefore, **one context variable per function suffices** even for multiple independent chains.\n\n7. **graph.cpp** (`#retro\\ops9kgra1st\\graph.cpp` L549, L1045):\n   This is a C++ file. The pattern `p_cp[i] = strtok(str1, \" \");` appears inside a for-loop. Context variable works the same way.\n\n8. **init.c has commented-out strtok_s already**: Lines like `//tokh_cp=strtok_s(buf_cp,\" ,\\t\\n\",&tokh_next);` -- these already use `strtok_s(` and do NOT match the denylist. When we replace the active `strtok(` on the line above, we should **also remove these now-redundant commented-out lines** since the active code itself becomes `strtok_s`. Or per minimal-change principle, leave them.\n\n---\n\n## Phase 7: Verification Strategy\n\n### Step 1: Run the denylist scan manually before committing\n```bash\ncd D:/refactoring/ops5k_x64\npython .hooks/pre_commit_denylist.py\n```\nThis scans all tracked `src/` files and reports violations. If it returns 0, all violations are cleared.\n\n### Step 2: Incremental per-phase commits\nCommit after each phase to enable targeted rollback if issues arise:\n1. Commit Phase 1 (ctime) -- 2 files\n2. Commit Phase 2 (localtime) -- 7 files\n3. Commit Phase 3 (gmtime) -- 11 files\n4. Commit Phase 4 (strerror) -- 9 files\n5. Commit Phase 5 (getenv) -- 22 files\n6. Commit Phase 6 (strtok) -- 38 files (could further split into sub-phases)\n\nEach commit is validated by the pre-commit hook automatically.\n\n### Step 3: Compile verification\nAfter each phase, attempt compilation with the project's build system. The `Build` directory suggests there is a build configuration. Compilation errors would reveal:\n- Missing variable declarations\n- Incorrect `->` to `.` conversions missed\n- Type mismatches\n\n### Step 4: Cross-reference counts\nAfter all changes, verify totals:\n- `grep -c` for each `_s` function should match the original unsafe function count\n- `grep -c` for each original unsafe function should be 0\n\n---\n\n## Implementation Order Summary\n\n| Priority | Phase | Function | Files | Occurrences | Complexity | Rationale |\n|----------|-------|----------|-------|-------------|------------|-----------|\n| 1 | Phase 1 | ctime | 2 | 4 | Low | Fewest files, establishes workflow |\n| 2 | Phase 2 | localtime | 7 | 12 | Low-Med | Mostly comments, 2 active |\n| 3 | Phase 3 | gmtime | 11 | 30 | Medium | Similar to localtime, more volume |\n| 4 | Phase 4 | strerror | 9 | 94 | Medium | Uniform pattern, single subsystem |\n| 5 | Phase 5 | getenv | 22 | 49 | Med-High | Inline usage needs extraction |\n| 6 | Phase 6 | strtok | 3